een built into our present chemical environments and future-oriented regulatory systems, why contaminants seem to always evade control, and why the Anthropocene is as inextricably harnessed to the synthesis of carbon into new molecules as it is driven by carbon’s combustion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChemical industryxEnvironmental aspects. 0aChemicalsxSafety measures. 0aChemistry, TechnicalxEnvironmental aspects. 0aChemistry, TechnicalxSocial aspects. 0aEnvironmental policy. 0aEnvironmental sociology. 0aPollution. 7aTechnology & Engineering / General.2bisacsh  achemicals, ecosystem, environment, industrial chemicals, biological persistence, economic, natural substances, Polychlorinated biphenyls, PCBs, asbestos, United Nations, UN, Green Cross, International Council of Chemical Trade Associations, global impact, chemicals production, residual materialism, chemical environments, minerals.1 aCreager, Angela N. H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aFrickel, Scott, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aJas, Nathalie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aReinhardt, Carsten, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aRoberts, Jody A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Engineering, Computer Sciences 2021 Englishz978311075407008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Engineering, Computer Sciences 2021z9783110753837oZDB-23-DEI08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University 